      <h2>Correction Model and Append-Only History</h2>
      <ShibuiContent id="the-actual-news.correction-model-and-append-only-history.p1">
	<span slot="entry">
		<p>I designed corrections as first-class immutable events rather than quiet edits. When a claim is corrected, the original stays intact, a new version is appended with updated evidence, and a correction event records who changed what and why. You can reconstruct the exact state of any story at any point in its history. Conformance test CT-07 enforces this: original records are never deleted or modified.</p>
	</span>
	<span slot="elevated">
		<p>
        Traditional news platforms handle corrections through quiet edits — the original text is silently replaced, and readers who saw the earlier version have no way to know what changed or why. The Actual News treats corrections as first-class immutable events in an <ShibuiTerm term="append-only log" definition="A data structure where new entries are only ever added to the end, never modified or deleted, preserving a complete and tamper-evident history" />. When a claim is corrected, the original claim is preserved with its original evidence graph, a new claim version is appended with updated evidence, and a correction event records the reason, the author, the timestamp, and the diff between old and new.<Cite id={3} author="Newman, Sam" title="Building Microservices: Designing Fine-Grained Systems" source="O'Reilly Media" year={2015} /> Newman's <ShibuiTerm term="event sourcing" definition="A persistence pattern that stores every state change as an immutable event rather than overwriting current state, enabling full history reconstruction" /> pattern — storing state changes as an immutable sequence of events rather than overwriting current state — provides the technical foundation: the claims ledger is not a mutable table but an append-only log where every state transition is recorded. This makes it possible to reconstruct the exact state of any story at any point in its history, including which evidence supported which claims at the time of original publication versus after correction. Conformance test CT-07 validates this invariant: it verifies that the correction mechanism never deletes or modifies original claim records, only appends new versions with correction metadata.
      </p>
	</span>
      </ShibuiContent>
      <button class="shibui-bridge" type="button">This section goes deeper</button>

      <CodeStructure lang="typescript" caption="Correction event handler — appends a new claim version while preserving the original, creating an auditable correction trail" filename="claim-service/src/handlers/correct-claim.ts">
{`interface CorrectionEvent {
  originalClaimId: string;
  correctedText: string;
  reason: string;
  newEvidence: EvidenceRef[];
  author: string;
  timestamp: Date;
}

async function correctClaim(
  event: CorrectionEvent,
  tx: Transaction
): Promise<ClaimVersion> {
  // Original claim is NEVER modified — only its status changes
  await tx.query(
    \`UPDATE claims SET support_status = 'corrected',
     corrected_at = $1 WHERE id = $2\`,
    [event.timestamp, event.originalClaimId]
  );

  // New version appended with full provenance
  const newVersion = await tx.query(
    \`INSERT INTO claim_versions
     (claim_id, version, text, confidence, evidence_refs,
      correction_reason, corrected_by, created_at)
     VALUES ($1, nextval('claim_version_seq'), $2, $3, $4, $5, $6, $7)
     RETURNING *\`,
    [
      event.originalClaimId,
      event.correctedText,
      0.0, // confidence resets — must be re-evaluated
      JSON.stringify(event.newEvidence),
      event.reason,
      event.author,
      event.timestamp,
    ]
  );

  // Correction event recorded in append-only audit log
  await tx.query(
    \`INSERT INTO correction_log
     (claim_id, old_version, new_version, reason, author, timestamp)
     VALUES ($1, $2, $3, $4, $5, $6)\`,
    [
      event.originalClaimId,
      newVersion.rows[0].version - 1,
      newVersion.rows[0].version,
      event.reason,
      event.author,
      event.timestamp,
    ]
  );

  return newVersion.rows[0];
}`}
      </CodeStructure>

      <h2>Database Design and Event-Driven Pipeline</h2>
      <ShibuiContent id="the-actual-news.database-design-and-event-driven-pipeline.p1">
	<span slot="entry">
		<p>I designed a PostgreSQL schema with ten domain tables plus an event outbox, all organized around the verification spine. Identity, content, evidence, claims, verification, and correction tables each own a distinct concern. The event outbox ensures publish events only fire if the transaction commits, and every table is scoped by platform ID so multiple newsrooms can run the same codebase with isolated data.</p>
	</span>
	<span slot="elevated">
		<p>
        The PostgreSQL schema consists of ten domain tables plus an event outbox, organized around the verification spine. Identity tables track platform participants (actors) and conflict-of-interest declarations with validity windows. Content tables store story containers with a draft/review/published state machine and immutable narrative version snapshots in Markdown. Evidence tables hold content-addressed objects with SHA-256 hashes and full provenance metadata. Claims tables store typed atomic statements with support status and confidence scores, connected to evidence through directed, weighted edges. Verification tables manage review task assignments and structured verdicts. Correction tables maintain the append-only event log. The event outbox implements a reliable emission pattern: publish events are inserted into the outbox within the same transaction that updates story state, ensuring that the event is guaranteed to emit if and only if the state change commits.<Cite id={3} author="Newman, Sam" title="Building Microservices: Designing Fine-Grained Systems" source="O'Reilly Media" year={2015} /> All objects are scoped by <code>platform_id</code>, enabling multi-tenant deployment from the same schema — a local civic newsroom and a national investigative platform can run the same codebase with different policy configurations and isolated data.
      </p>
	</span>
      </ShibuiContent>
