      <h2>Ten-Phase Roadmap</h2>
      <p>
        The project follows a ten-phase roadmap from prototype to archival permanence, with the north star metric of verified-information-throughput — verified claim throughput per unit cost, with corrections as a first-class improvement signal rather than an embarrassment to be minimized. Phase 0 (Foundations) freezes contracts and establishes the local development loop. Phase 1 (MVP Local Civic Beat) completes the end-to-end story lifecycle: ingest, verify, publish, correct. Phases 2 through 4 build the trust engine, operations posture, and attention-decoupled economics. Phase 5 introduces federation — two independent deployments exchanging story bundles with verifiable consistency. Phases 6 and 7 extend the platform to public institutions (libraries, cities, schools) and specialized reporting (investigations, datasets, media provenance). Phase 8 hardens governance for cooperative or endowment stewardship. Phase 9 (Back Again) ensures archival permanence — a third party can reconstruct the full archive from exports alone. The project currently stands at Phase 0, with contracts frozen, database schema stable, gateway operational, and all seven conformance tests passing.<Cite id={7} author="Ostrom, Elinor" title="Governing the Commons: The Evolution of Institutions for Collective Action" source="Cambridge University Press" year={1990} />
      </p>

      <h2>Economic Model and the AGPL Mandate</h2>
      <ShibuiContent id="the-actual-news.economic-model-and-the-agpl-mandate.p1">
	<span slot="entry">
		<p>I built the economics around verification rather than attention. The evidence graph is the monetizable asset -- institutions and researchers subscribe to structured, verified claims rather than paying for reader eyeballs. The AGPL license enforces the same transparency principle at the code level: a platform built on the premise that evidence should be transparent cannot itself be opaque. Any deployment must share its source, preventing proprietary forks from weakening verification standards.</p>
	</span>
	<span slot="elevated">
		<p>
        The economic model follows from the architecture: if value comes from verification rather than attention, then funding can decouple from advertising and click-through metrics. A platform whose product is the evidence graph — the structured, machine-readable justification for every claim — creates value that compounds over time as the graph grows, rather than depreciating as news cycles move on. Zuboff's analysis of surveillance capitalism demonstrates the structural problem with attention-based models: when user engagement is the product, the platform's economic incentive is to maximize time-on-site through emotional provocation rather than informational accuracy.<Cite id={9} author="Zuboff, Shoshana" title="The Age of Surveillance Capitalism" source="PublicAffairs" year={2019} /> The Actual News inverts this by making the evidence graph the monetizable asset — institutions, researchers, and other newsrooms can subscribe to the structured data feed, paying for verified claims and their provenance chains rather than for reader eyeballs. Benkler's framework for <ShibuiTerm term="commons-based peer production" definition="Yochai Benkler's model of collaborative creation where participants contribute to a shared resource without traditional market or firm coordination" /> provides the theoretical grounding for the licensing choice: the <ShibuiTerm term="AGPL" definition="GNU Affero General Public License -- a copyleft license that requires anyone running modified software over a network to publish their source code" /> ensures that any deployment of the platform must share its source code, including modifications, creating a transparency mandate that mirrors the platform's editorial principles.<Cite id={10} author="Benkler, Yochai" title="The Wealth of Networks: How Social Production Transforms Markets and Freedom" source="Yale University Press" year={2006} /> A platform built on the premise that evidence should be transparent cannot itself be opaque. The AGPL makes this principle legally enforceable — any organization running a modified version must publish their modifications, preventing proprietary forks that might weaken the verification requirements while trading on the platform's reputation for rigor.
      </p>
	</span>
      </ShibuiContent>
